text.full: Casual, sit down, full service sushi restaurant across from King Ed station.  Service was nice and friendly.  All the regular items here, everything was good - nothing extraordinary but a solid meal.  Quite busy at dinner time.  A little drafty near the door, but I suppose that's to be expected.

We enjoyed the food here. Because of the exchange rate, prices were great. 

Our rolls, sushi and sashimi all tasted very good. 

The only problem is that there are just too many options in Vancouver, so although we wanted too, we never made it back.

Korean was calling our stomachs.
Tasty and juicy Rosu Katsu, cabbage salad is great, for sure will come back again. Great customer service. If the rice served in warm and moist will be perfect.

I came here after seeing it listed as one of those 'must-try' cafes in Vancouver. The architecture is definitely unique--it has a flower-like exterior, and inside, it's airy and cozy with a design that almost resembles mushroom gills. It creates a refreshing atmosphere that feels open yet intimate.

The cafe has limited hours, which may cater more to the nearby student crowd at Emily Carr University. They're open Monday to Friday from 8 am to 4 pm, and on weekends from 9 am to 5 pm. I ordered the Spicy Hot Chocolate, but honestly, I didn't find it noteworthy, and I probably wouldn't make a special trip back. Their seasonal options like the Hojicha Maple Latte do look fun, though a bit pricey at $7.50.

The interior and exterior are standouts among Vancouver's cafes, and the staff were friendly, which added to the pleasant vibe. If you plan to visit, I'd suggest coming earlier in the day to get the best selection from their baked goods section.
Delicious açai bowls and smoothies! Tried the smoothie for the first time and it was quite refreshing.

We ordered the veggie spring rolls, scallion pancake, and salt and pepper chicken. The salt and pepper chicken was definitely the standout--crispy, flavorful, and perfectly cooked. The veggie spring rolls came with a delicious plum sauce that added a nice touch, although I found the rolls a bit on the salty side.

One of the best things about this spot is the late hours. They're open until 12:30 am, and we appreciated that they didn't turn us away when we arrived right at midnight. It's a convenient option if you're looking for a solid late-night bite with friendly service.

Deer Lake Park is truly one of my favorite parks in Vancouver! The path that circles the park offers beautiful views of the lake almost the entire way, making it a relaxing and scenic walk. It's conveniently located next to Burnaby Village Museum, so it's easy to combine both for a lovely day out. While there aren't many food options nearby (aside from the museum bakery), you won't need much time here unless you're picnicking. Walking the full loop takes about an hour, so be sure to bring water.

I usually start from Oakland Street near Baffin Place. It's a slight slope down into the park, but nothing too strenuous. The trails are well-signposted, with part of the route taking you along a charming boardwalk. The Festival Lawn is also a great feature of the park. We got to see Vampire Weekend perform there over the summer, which was amazing! It's perfect for spreading out a blanket and enjoying the concert vibes, with plenty of food trucks around to try. Just be aware that leaving after an event can be a bit challenging due to traffic routing and crowding.

Overall, Deer Lake Park is a must-visit, especially on a nice day. Whether you're there to take a stroll, enjoy nature, or catch a concert, it's a spot that never disappoints!
Food was good but slightly on the expensive side. Service was excellent, will go back again.

Although it can be a bit pricy, this is a great place to shop for special occasions (hosting over the holidays) or small gifts! It's fun to see all the different flavours and speciality products they have compared to a grocery or drug store. #ContestEntry
